	<title>Direction Angles: Examples</title>
	<showme>
		<statement>
			<para>Find the direction angles of the vector <latex>\Vect{x} = (3,4)</latex> in <latex>\RNr[2]</latex>.</para>
		</statement>
		
		<answer type="Solution">
			<para>We have <latex>| \Vect{x} | = 5</latex>, and 
				<subordinate>
					<hot>so</hot>
					<info>
						<caption>What are we going to use to make this computation</caption>
						<para>Remember the formula for the first direction angle:</para>
						<math.display>
							<latex>\omega_1 = \arccos \frac{x_1}{ | \Vect{x} | }</latex>
						</math.display>
					</info>
				</subordinate>,
			</para>
			
			<math.display>
				<latex>\omega_1 = \arccos \frac{3}{5} \approx 53.1\quad \text{degrees}</latex>
			</math.display>
			
			<para>To find <latex>\omega_2 </latex> we now have two possible approaches. The first approach just uses the
				<subordinate>
					<hot>formula for direction angles</hot>
					<info>
						<caption>Recall the formula for the second direction angle</caption>
						
						<math.display>
							<latex>\omega_2 = \arccos \frac{x_2}{ | \Vect{x} | }</latex>
						</math.display>
					</info>
				</subordinate>
				again:</para>
			
			<math.display>
				<latex>\omega_2 = \arccos \frac{4}{5} \approx 36.9\quad \text{degrees}</latex>
			</math.display>
			
			<para>In the second approach we 
				<subordinate>
					<hot>observe that</hot>
					<info>
						<caption>What does it tell us if <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> is a first quadrant vector?</caption>
						<para>The direction angles of a first quadrant vector in <latex>\RNr[2]</latex> add up to <latex>90</latex> degrees.</para>
						
						<para align="center"><img src="ims/DirectionAnglesR2.gif" width="343" height="237"/></para>
					</info>
				</subordinate>
				 <latex>\Vect{x}</latex> is a first quadrant vector. Therefore</para>
			
			<para align="center"><latex>\omega_1 + \omega_2 = 90</latex>, and so, <latex>\omega_2 \approx 90 - 53.1 = 36.9\quad \text{degrees}</latex>.</para>
		</answer>
	</showme>
	
	
	
	<showme>
		<statement>
			<para>Find the cosines of the direction angles of <latex>\Vect{u} = (-1,1,1)</latex> in <latex>\RNr[3]</latex>.</para>
		</statement>
		
		<answer type="Solution">
			<para>We have <latex>\Vect{u} = \sqrt{3}</latex>, and so</para>
			<computation>
				<left>\cos \omega_1</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>- \dfrac{1}{ \sqrt{3} }</right>
				<left>\cos \omega_2</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>\dfrac{1}{ \sqrt{3} }</right>
				<left>\cos \omega_3</left>
				<center>=</center>
				<right>\dfrac{1}{ \sqrt{3} }</right>
			</computation>
		</answer>
	</showme>
